This function will be responsible for converting a job sequence into a detailed operation schedule with start/end times
allocate_ops_to_machines(job_sequence, proc_times, M)
J = number of jobs (job_sequence.size())
N = number of operations per job (width of proc_times - 1)

machines_available = number of machines available
job_ops = the current operation a job is on (job[0 … n])

schedule = empty 2D array

For jobs j in job_sequence:
	For ops o in N:
		//Assign an operation to a machine using o mod M
			m = o mod M
            //we can only assign a new operation if the machine is not busy,  and the previous job is complete
			If machines_available[m] is not busy AND job_ops[o-1] is done:
				//start the operation!
				machines_available[m] = o
                job_ops(o) = busy
				start = process_operation(o) //signals that this operation has started, and when the operation has started processing

				end = start + proc_times[j][o]

				//populate schedule
				schedule[j][o] = (m,j,start,end) //store machine, job, start and end times

				//make machine available again
				machines_available[m] = free
				//inform operation is done
				job_ops[o] = free

return schedule //return operation schedule



What is a makespan? - The maximum completion time across all jobs/operations.
Returns the makespan value of a single job/operation
compute_makespan(schedule)
